recipeIngredients:
• Non-fat plain Greek yogurt, 7 oz(s), about 1 cup (7oz)
  • Muesli, ½ cup(s) (1.5oz)
  • Strawberries, ½ cup(s), sliced (2.9oz)
  • Mango, ½ cup(s), pieces (2.9oz)
  • Shelled pumpkin seeds, 1 tbsp(s) (0.3oz)
recipeInstructions:
Spoon ¼ cup of yogurt into the base of a glass or jar. Top with 1½ tablespoons of muesli, a few sliced strawberries and pieces of mango.

Repeat the layers, finishing with remaining yogurt, strawberries and mango. Sprinkle with seeds.

TIP: Any type of unsalted seeds will work for e.g sesame, sunflower. Muesli is a healthier lower sugar and fat alternative to granola. To save time during the week prepare 2 to 3 jars with lids and store in the fridge for a quick breakfast during the week.

recipeIngredients:
• Tuna, canned in water, 3 oz(s), drained (3oz)
  • Moroccan seasoning, 1 tsp(s) (0.1oz)
  • Rye crispbread, 4 crispbread(s) (1.4oz)
  • Tomato, ½ medium, whole, chopped (2.2oz)
  • Avocado, 2 tbsp(s), mashed (1.1oz)
  • Carrot, shredded, ¼ cup(s) (1oz)
  • Cucumber, ½ medium, chopped (3.5oz)
  • Red onion, chopped, 1½ tbsp(s) (0.5oz)
  • Red wine vinegar, 1 tsp(s) (0.2oz)
  • Black pepper, 1 dash(es)
recipeInstructions:
Mix tuna and seasoning in a bowl and spread evenly over crispbreads.

Mix tomato, avocado, carrot, cucumber, onion and vinegar together.

Spread tomato mixture over tuna on crispbreads. Season to taste.

TIP: If you are unable to find Moroccan seasoning in the supermarket, you can make your own using this recipe: Moroccan spice blend.

recipeIngredients:
• Brussels sprouts, 8 sprout(s), halved (5.4oz)
  • Extra virgin olive oil, 1 tsp(s) (0.2oz)
  • Carrots, 1 medium, cut into rounds (2.2oz)
  • Red onion, ¼ small, sliced (0.5oz)
  • Garlic, minced, 1 tsp(s) (0.1oz)
  • Chicken breast, raw, 3 oz(s), diced (3oz)
  • Shelled pumpkin seeds, 1 tsp(s) (0.1oz)
  • Black pepper, 1 dash(es), to taste
recipeInstructions:
In a bowl of boiling water, blanch the Brussels sprouts for 30 seconds. Drain and set aside.

Heat half of the olive oil in a large skillet or wok to medium heat. Add Brussels sprouts and carrot. Stir fry for 5 to 6 minutes or until vegetables begin to soften. Once softened, place in a bowl and cover.

Add remaining oil to pan, turn heat up to medium-high and add onion and garlic. Cook for 1 minute or until fragrant.

Add chicken and cook for 8 to 10 minutes or until golden and cooked through. Once cooked, add cooked vegetables back into pan and stir fry for 2 minutes and remove from heat.

Spoon into a bowl to serve, sprinkle with pumpkin seeds and season to taste.

TIP: To save time, cook double this recipe and refrigerate one portion in an airtight container to reheat for dinner later in the week.

recipeIngredients:
• Beets, cooked, 2 small beet(s), cut into thin wedges (3.5oz)
  • Extra virgin olive oil, 2 tsp(s) (0.3oz)
  • Black pepper, 1 dash(es)
  • Carrots, 2 medium, cut into 1-inch pieces (4.3oz)
  • Brussels sprouts, 6 sprout(s), trimmed and sliced (4oz)
  • Moroccan seasoning, 6 tsp(s) (0.4oz)
  • Red onion, 1 small, cut into thin wedges (2.1oz)
  • Lamb loin, choice, very lean, 6 oz(s) (6oz)
  • Red wine vinegar, 2 tbsp(s) (1.1oz)
  • Fresh mint, 2 tbsp(s) (0.1oz)
recipeInstructions:
Prepare Moroccan lamb with spiced vegetables according to recipe instructions below.

Serve half the recipe for dinner and place other half into an airtight container in the fridge for use later in the week.

Moroccan lamb with spiced vegetables instructions

Preheat oven 425°F. Place beets in small roasting pan. Drizzle lightly with a ½ teaspoon of olive oil and season to taste.

In another roasting pan, arrange carrots and Brussels sprouts. Drizzle lightly with a ½ teaspoon of olive oil, sprinkle with 4 teaspoons of the spice mix, and turn to coat. Place both pans into the oven and roast for 20 minutes.

Remove both pans of vegetables from the oven. Add onions to the beets, stir to combine. Roast a further 10 minutes. Remove from oven.

Meanwhile, rub lamb lightly with 1 teaspoon of olive oil and sprinkle with remaining 2 teaspoons spice mix.. Heat a non-stick skillet over medium heat. Add lamb, cook for 4 minutes each side, for medium, or until cooked to your liking. Remove to a plate, cover with foil to keep warm. Allow the lamb to stand for 10 minutes before thickly slicing.

Add the beets to the carrots pan. Spoon over the vinegar. Top with the lamb and any pan juices from resting. Scatter over the mint to serve.

TIP: Feel free to swap the lamb for lean beef steak. If you are unable to find Moroccan seasoning in the supermarket, you can make your own using this recipe: Moroccan spice blend.

recipeIngredients:
• Carrots, 2 medium, sliced lengthways (4.3oz)
  • Baby broccoli (broccolini), ½ cup(s), chopped (1.4oz)
  • Extra virgin olive oil, 1 tsp(s) (0.2oz)
  • Curry powder, 1 tsp(s) (0.1oz)
  • Whitefish, raw, 3 oz(s) (3oz)
recipeInstructions:
Preheat oven to 425°F.

Toss carrots and broccolini in ½ tsp of olive oil and the curry powder. When oven is heated, roast carrots for 20 minutes or until carrots are caramelized and tender. Roast broccolini for 10 minutes. Season to taste.

Meanwhile, heat remaining oil in a non-stick frying pan over medium to high heat.

Season fish and cook for 4 to 5 minutes each side or until cooked through.

To serve, plate fish with carrots and broccolini.

TIP: Season fish with pepper or any other seasoning you like for example, cumin, paprika or lemon and garlic. Add lemon wedges, to serve.

recipeIngredients:
• Banana, 1 medium, ripe, mashed (4.2oz)
  • Eggs, 2 large (3.5oz)
  • Vanilla extract, 1 tsp(s) (0.1oz)
  • Muesli, ½ cup(s) (1.5oz)
  • Cinnamon, ground, 1 tsp(s) (0.1oz)
  • Peanut butter, reduced sugar & salt, 1½ tsp(s) (0.3oz)
recipeInstructions:
In a large bowl, add banana, eggs and vanilla. Mix until well combined. Mix in muesli and cinnamon.

Heat a skillet over medium heat and pour in half a cup of the pancake batter. Spread slightly to form an even layer. Cook for 2 to 3 minutes until you start to see bubbles appearing from the top of the batter. Flip and cook for 1 to 2 minutes, until the other side is golden brown. Remove from heat and set aside.

Repeat with the remaining half of batter. 

Drizzle peanut butter over pancakes.

TIP: Feel free to swap the peanut butter for any other preferred nut butter or, for a crunchier meal, opt for chopped nuts like pecans or walnuts.
